Thousands of men, like the leaves and the flowers that come in the springtime.Iliad2, 468.
The Acropolis is full in a trice as they
noisily settle in place,
Iliad2, 463.
and everywhere are begging-bags and flattery, beards and shamelessness, staves and gluttony, syllogisms and avarice. The few that came up in answer to the first summons are obscure and inconspicuous, intermingled with the crowd of others, and they escape the eye in the general similarity of garb.
